d renal blood flow","Decreased prostaglandin production","Afferent arteriole vasoconstriction","Reduced medullary blood flow"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the first phase (0-2 hours) of unilateral ureteric obstruction, there is \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased renal blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E due to prostaglandin-mediated vasodilation of the afferent arteriole. This occurs despite rising intraluminal pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased renal blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the second phase (2-4 hours) due to vasoconstriction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased prostaglandin production\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as prostaglandins are increased during the early phase, mediating vasodilation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAfferent arteriole vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in later phases, not during the initial response\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced medullary blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E is a later consequence of the obstruction\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initial vasodilatory response is thought to be protective, though it is followed by vasoconstriction if the obstruction persists beyond 2-4 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In early ureteric obstruction (0-2 hours), increased intraluminal pressure causes increased renal blood flow through prostaglandin-mediated vasodilation","The initial vasodilatory phase of ureteric obstruction is followed by vasoconstriction and reduced renal blood flow after 2-4 hours","Prostaglandin production increases in early obstruction, causing afferent arteriole vasodilation"],"references":["Ucero AC, Benito-Martin A, Izquierdo MC, Sanchez-Ni\u00f1o MD, Sanz AB, Ramos AM, Berzal S, Ruiz-Ortega M, Egido J, Ortiz A. Unilateral ureteral obstruction: beyond obstruction. Int Urol Nephrol. 2014 Apr;46(4):765-76. doi: 10.1007/s11255-013-0520-1. Epub 2013 Sep 27. PMID: 24072452.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53374"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15087"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53374"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:34:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:35:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7775"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio